 :::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::: 📓DEV NOTE ::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
 🏪 OVERVIEW OF CLI
 ` TARES_CLI is a cli terminal word scrumble multipler game built with Golang enabling websocket connections 
 from the terminal. Multiple user connect and and when a user joins, the game manager (another aspect of the game)
 connects the users to an available room. If no rooms are available current, or no player is online, current user can 
 connect later or request to wait in line.
 User can also opt to play singularly , by which the points they earned are half what's earned in a multiplayer mode 
 There will be a CREED BOARD - of all users and their standings from the first to the the 100th
 #Scores users accumulate is the determinant of the position on the BOARD
 # Scores are measures of difficulty of level: 
   - Player modes have a base score + a force-multiplier- (a percentage of players 
   in room where score was obtained - *(n-1))
 ` 
 BUILD PHILOSOPHY:
 - Server first, completely ---> Test with wscat ---> Client second
 # Depending on the level, isolation allows for targeted 
 
 HIGH LEVEL CONCEPTUALISATION OF WHAT MUST BE DONE AT THE END OF EACH DAY
  - Day 1 → Foundation          (Project structure + WebSocket server + message types)
  - Day 2 → Game Brain          (Rooms + matchmaking + shared state)
  - Day 3 → Game Logic          (Word validation + scoring + timer)
  - Day 4 → The Client          (CLI connection + terminal renderer)
  - Day 5 → Polish + REST API   (Stats + leaderboard + demo-ready)

  -------------- DETAILED DAY ACTIVITIES ------------------------------
   - DAY 1
     Morning (2-3 hours) — Concepts + Setup
       - Understand Go modules (go.mod) vs Node's package.json
       - Understand Go's package system (internal/ and why it exists)
       - Project scaffolding
       - go.mod initialization
       - Install dependencies (gorilla/websocket)
       - Understand what gorilla/websocket actually does vs raw Go net/http

     Afternoon (2-3 hours) — Build
       - shared/messages/types.go    ← every message type defined here
       - server/internal/player/message.go  ← reading/writing messages
       - server/internal/player/client.go   ← one goroutine per connection
       - server/main.go              ← HTTP server + WebSocket upgrade

   - DAY 2
       Morning (2-3 hours) — Concepts
       - What a race condition actually looks like in practice
         (we'll trigger one intentionally so you see it crash)
       - sync.Mutex — when and why
       - Go maps and why map[string]int is not safe concurrently
       - The matchmaking pattern (a waiting queue)
     
      Afternoon (2-3 hours) — Build
       - server/internal/game/room.go      ← Room struct + mutex
       - server/internal/game/manager.go   ← RoomManager + matchmaking queue
       - Wire manager into player connection handler
       - Player joins → goes into waiting queue
       - Second player joins → both pulled into a room
       - Both receive "start" message with letters and opponent name

   - DAY 3
      Morning (2-3 hours) — Concepts + Word Validation
       - Embedding files in Go binary (the dictionary)
       - Why word validation has a race condition 
         (two players, same word, same millisecond)
       - How context.Context works and why Go uses it everywhere
       - Goroutine lifecycle — what a goroutine leak is
       
      Aternoon (2-3 hours) — Build
       - data/words.txt              ← dictionary file
       - server/internal/game/validator.go  ← word validation logic
         - Is it a real word?
         - Can these letters make this word?
         - Was it already used by either player?
       - server/internal/game/room.go (expand)
         - Score tracking
         - Used words set (mutex protected)
         - Broadcast to both players
       - server/internal/game/timer.go
         - 60 second countdown goroutine
         - Sends time updates every 10 seconds
         - Ends game when timer hits zero

    - DAY 4
       Morning (2-3 hours) — Concepts + Setup
         - The Elm Architecture (Model, Update, View) — bubbletea's model
         - How bubbletea's event loop works
         - WebSocket client in Go (same library, opposite direction)
         - How client state machine works:
            connecting → waiting → playing → game over
       
       Afternoon (2-3 hours) — Build
         - client/internal/connection.go
           - Connect to server via WebSocket
           - Receive messages → convert to bubbletea events
           - Send messages when player submits word
         - client/internal/state.go
           - Client-side game state (scores, letters, words, timer)
           - State transitions based on server messages
         - client/internal/renderer.go
           - The terminal UI layout
           - Letters display
           - Score comparison
           - Word input field
           - Timer display
         - client/main.go
           - Parse --name and --server flags
           - Wire connection + bubbletea together
    - DAY 5
         Morning (2-3 hours) — REST API + Stats
           - server/internal/stats/tracker.go
             - In-memory stats (mutex protected)
             - Track: games played, words submitted, top scores
             - Updates after every game ends
           - server/internal/api/routes.go
           - server/internal/api/handlers.go
           Endpoints:
             GET /health          → server status, active games count
             GET /stats           → total games, words played today
             GET /leaderboard     → top 10 scores with player names
           Test all three with curl
           
           Aternoon (2-3 hours) — Polish + Documentation
           - Error handling audit (what if player sends malformed JSON?)
           - Graceful server shutdown (SIGTERM handling)
           - Makefile targets:
               make server   → builds and runs server
               make client   → builds and runs client
               make both     → runs server + two clients (demo mode)
           - README with:
               Architecture diagram
               How to run
               What Go concepts it demonstrates
               Message protocol documentation






